01:03:31,073 --> 01:03:34,804
I got two sets
of bleachers on my set

1220
01:03:34,844 --> 01:03:37,039
where visitors
could sit and watch.

1221
01:03:37,079 --> 01:03:41,015
My crew loved it.
They were as big a ham as I am.

1222
01:03:41,050 --> 01:03:44,747
They had fun watching me
as the director.

1223
01:03:44,787 --> 01:03:46,812
- (plays a chord)
- (sings off-key, laughing)

1224
01:03:46,856 --> 01:03:49,120
Then they had fun
watching me as the comic.

1225
01:03:49,158 --> 01:03:50,853
(laughing)
Cut.

1226
01:03:50,893 --> 01:03:52,884
They'd see me
run into myself.

1227
01:03:52,929 --> 01:03:55,056
- (laughing)
- Cut.

1228
01:03:55,097 --> 01:03:57,998
It's a challenge,
when you're feeling all of this power

1229
01:03:58,034 --> 01:04:01,731
that you have to have
and delegate to the right people,

1230
01:04:01,771 --> 01:04:04,137
to keep yourself calm
to give a performance.

1231
01:04:04,173 --> 01:04:07,301
Woody Harrelson: The camaraderie
had to be important for him

1232
01:04:07,343 --> 01:04:10,471
just to be able to feel like
he could just let go

1233
01:04:10,513 --> 01:04:14,176
and do some of that
wild insanity that he would...

1234
01:04:14,217 --> 01:04:16,048
he'd come up with
just the most...

1235
01:04:16,085 --> 01:04:18,144
(truck horn blows)

1236
01:04:18,187 --> 01:04:19,654
Argh!

1237
01:04:19,689 --> 01:04:22,658
You have to feel safe
to be able to do that.

1238
01:04:22,692 --> 01:04:24,990
(crew laughing)

1239
01:04:26,996 --> 01:04:29,021
Son of a bitch.

1240
01:04:29,065 --> 01:04:31,226
Will you leave me alone?

1241
01:04:31,267 --> 01:04:34,395
It just seemed like
the most fun you could have...

1242
01:04:34,437 --> 01:04:37,964
in the '60s at Paramount,
doing his thing.

1243
01:04:38,007 --> 01:04:39,474
Man: 310-2.

1244
01:04:39,508 --> 01:04:42,068
And one day
I read in the paper

1245
01:04:42,111 --> 01:04:44,978
that a motion picture
advertiser needed help.

1246
01:04:45,014 --> 01:04:46,777
(sighs)

1247
01:04:46,816 --> 01:04:48,841
- Do you have to go to the toilet?
- (crew snickering)

1248
01:04:48,885 --> 01:04:50,182
- No.
- No?

1249
01:04:50,219 --> 01:04:53,245
- I'm just fine.
- (laughter)

1250
01:04:53,289 --> 01:04:54,654
All right, cut.

1251
01:04:54,690 --> 01:04:57,318
I have to tell you this

1252
01:04:57,360 --> 01:05:00,056
because I can't keep it
to myself any longer.

1253
01:05:00,096 --> 01:05:02,656
I was in New York
three weeks ago,

1254
01:05:02,698 --> 01:05:04,962
couldn't get a cab.
It was raining.

1255
01:05:05,001 --> 01:05:07,162
So I go downstairs
to the subway

1256
01:05:07,203 --> 01:05:09,194
and I get on the train.

1257
01:05:09,238 --> 01:05:12,503
I'm sitting there
and it makes one stop.

1258
01:05:12,541 --> 01:05:14,975
And this guy gets on

1259
01:05:15,011 --> 01:05:17,138
wearing leather pants,

1260
01:05:17,179 --> 01:05:19,579
leather jacket,

1261
01:05:19,615 --> 01:05:23,415
leather shirt, leather tie,
leather boots.

1262
01:05:23,452 --> 01:05:27,980
And he had rings on his ears,
on his nose, on his lip.

1263
01:05:28,024 --> 01:05:31,653
And he had his hair
swiped up

1264
01:05:31,694 --> 01:05:34,720
yellow, red,

1265
01:05:34,764 --> 01:05:37,790
green, purple.

1266
01:05:37,833 --> 01:05:39,824
And he sits down
right opposite me.

1267
01:05:39,869 --> 01:05:41,860
And I'm staring at him.

1268
01:05:41,904 --> 01:05:43,895
He says, "What's the matter,
old man?

1269
01:05:43,940 --> 01:05:46,500
Didn't you ever see
anything strange before?"

1270
01:05:46,542 --> 01:05:50,069
I said, "Yeah, about 20 years ago
I had sex with a parrot.

1271
01:05:50,112 --> 01:05:52,103
I thought you were my son."

1272
01:05:52,148 --> 01:05:54,480
(laughter and applause)

1273
01:05:57,920 --> 01:06:01,378
This is just another thing
of his amazing eye.

1274
01:06:01,424 --> 01:06:02,789
(explosion)

1275
01:06:02,825 --> 01:06:04,816
Man:
Get the door!

1276
01:06:06,028 --> 01:06:08,826
(door squeaks)

1277
01:06:13,636 --> 01:06:17,128
Seinfeld: When he gets called
into the dean's office

1278
01:06:17,173 --> 01:06:20,006
as Professor Kelp
after the explosion

1279
01:06:20,042 --> 01:06:22,875
and he sits down
in that chair

1280
01:06:22,912 --> 01:06:26,211
and sinks into it...

1281
01:06:26,248 --> 01:06:28,716
to have the eye to know,

1282
01:06:28,751 --> 01:06:31,117
"This will look funny."

1283
01:06:31,153 --> 01:06:34,213
He's not doing anything.
He's just sinking

1284
01:06:34,256 --> 01:06:36,247
in a chair.

1285
01:06:36,292 --> 01:06:38,283
It's brilliant.

1286
01:06:38,327 --> 01:06:40,921
It's so funny.
It's so simple.

1287
01:06:40,963 --> 01:06:43,431
When I first started watching it,
I just know,

1288
01:06:43,466 --> 01:06:45,661
"This guy is making me laugh
every time I see him."

1289
01:06:45,701 --> 01:06:49,193
And now, having done
a few things myself,

1290
01:06:49,238 --> 01:06:51,968
I understand a lot more

1291
01:06:52,008 --> 01:06:53,999
and I appreciate

1292
01:06:54,043 --> 01:06:58,946
the incredible richness
of his skills even more.

1293
01:07:00,216 --> 01:07:02,616
Look at the headline
of the column.

1294
01:07:07,089 --> 01:07:08,989
- Are you in focus?
- Man: I am.

1295
01:07:09,025 --> 01:07:11,994
Good. 'Cause I like this kind of stuff
to be in focus.

1296
01:07:12,028 --> 01:07:14,792
(laughing)

1297
01:07:14,830 --> 01:07:17,025
The thrill of getting an idea

1298
01:07:17,066 --> 01:07:20,092
and then sketching it
and then sitting behind a camera,

1299
01:07:20,136 --> 01:07:23,799
and you're looking
and you see it's exact, let's shoot it...

1300
01:07:23,839 --> 01:07:27,275
it's a rush.
You want to do it some more.

1301
01:07:27,309 --> 01:07:30,767
(jazz orchestra playing)

1302
01:07:30,813 --> 01:07:32,906
I wanted to see the kid

1303
01:07:32,948 --> 01:07:35,508
- in a boardinghouse.
- (knocks)

1304
01:07:35,551 --> 01:07:37,815
Well, when you start
with an idea like this,

1305
01:07:37,853 --> 01:07:40,014
it just blooms.

1306
01:07:40,056 --> 01:07:42,115
So I built this set.

1307
01:07:42,158 --> 01:07:44,786
And it cost me almost a half a million
to build it.

1308
01:07:44,827 --> 01:07:47,660
We're talking about 1960.

1309
01:07:47,696 --> 01:07:49,687
All my sound...

1310
01:07:49,732 --> 01:07:52,223
everything was in the ceilings.

1311
01:07:52,268 --> 01:07:55,294
- Man: Let's try to get a microphone...
- One, two, three, four...

1312
01:07:55,337 --> 01:07:58,204
Jerry Lewis: I had three mixers
on the set

1313
01:07:58,240 --> 01:08:01,266
to cover the 42 rooms.

1314
01:08:02,945 --> 01:08:05,573
Spielberg: Those humongous sets
on "Ladies' Man,"

1315
01:08:05,614 --> 01:08:09,209
in a sense, rivaling
"The Diary of Anne Frank" set

1316
01:08:09,251 --> 01:08:11,617
and "The Rear Window"
Hitchcock set,

1317
01:08:11,654 --> 01:08:13,451
you know,
where it was all there.

1318
01:08:13,489 --> 01:08:16,549
It was all there for a filmmaker
to make choices.

1319
01:08:16,592 --> 01:08:19,288
Just pull back... you had it all
right before your lens.

1320
01:08:21,831 --> 01:08:24,698
They asked me if I would want

1321
01:08:24,733 --> 01:08:27,896
to teach a class at USC.

1322
01:08:27,937 --> 01:08:31,805
And I thought
that sounded terrific.

1323
01:08:31,841 --> 01:08:34,241
And I went for it.

1324
01:08:34,276 --> 01:08:38,736
And I had
eight magnificent years

1325
01:08:38,781 --> 01:08:42,581
teaching post-grad students.

1326
01:08:42,618 --> 01:08:44,711
He believed in young people.
And he believed

1327
01:08:44,753 --> 01:08:47,085
in a whole new generation
of filmmakers coming up.

1328
01:08:47,123 --> 01:08:50,183
And he had a class.
For young filmmakers.

1329
01:08:50,226 --> 01:08:52,854
And I had made "Amblin"'...
my short film.

1330
01:08:52,895 --> 01:08:55,455
And he invited me
to show the film to the class

1331
01:08:55,498 --> 01:08:57,830
and to speak about my process.

1332
01:08:57,867 --> 01:09:00,165
In my case,
being a fan of Jerry's,

1333
01:09:00,202 --> 01:09:02,193
almost feeling like
pinching myself...

1334
01:09:02,238 --> 01:09:03,830
I can't believe
I'm in the same room

1335
01:09:03,873 --> 01:09:06,171
and Jerry Lewis is actually
having a conversation with me.

1336
01:09:06,208 --> 01:09:08,768
Jerry Lewis:
Spielberg was in that class.

1337
01:09:08,811 --> 01:09:11,575
- Bogdanovich.
- Bogdanovich was in the class,

1338
01:09:11,614 --> 01:09:13,605
Randy Kleiser.

1339
01:09:13,649 --> 01:09:15,640
He was warm.
He was embracing.

1340
01:09:15,684 --> 01:09:17,549
He was funny.
He was serious.

1341
01:09:17,586 --> 01:09:19,850
When he taught at USC

1342
01:09:19,889 --> 01:09:21,982
and we were in his class,

1343
01:09:22,024 --> 01:09:24,185
he recorded those classes,

1344
01:09:24,226 --> 01:09:27,559
which ultimately became the book
"The Total Film-Maker."

1345
01:09:27,596 --> 01:09:30,087
Jerry Lewis:
Marty Scorsese

1346
01:09:30,132 --> 01:09:33,397
never went on the set
without the book.

1347
01:09:33,435 --> 01:09:36,302
I would argue with him about something,
he said, "Hold on a second."

1348
01:09:36,338 --> 01:09:39,102
So he'd lean over and
he'd turn pages in my book.

1349
01:09:39,141 --> 01:09:41,041
Spielberg:
And he loved those kids.

1350
01:09:41,076 --> 01:09:42,907
I mentor now to this day.

1351
01:09:42,945 --> 01:09:45,648
Jerry Lewis taught me
the importance of mentoring.

1352
01:09:45,648 --> 01:09:48,082
Harrelson:
The main reason I'm a performer

1353
01:09:48,117 --> 01:09:49,812
is because of Jerry.

1354
01:09:49,852 --> 01:09:51,752
He speaks
to the common man.

1355
01:09:51,787 --> 01:09:53,778
All I wanted to do
is apologize to you, see?

1356
01:09:53,822 --> 01:09:56,017
Will you get out of here?
If you don't, I'm gonna...

1357
01:09:56,058 --> 01:09:58,322
- Argh!
- Oh, wait, my foot.

1358
01:09:58,360 --> 01:10:00,521
- My foot is stuck.
- Get out of here.

1359
01:10:00,563 --> 01:10:02,531
Harrelson: You love him.
You root for him...

1360
01:10:02,565 --> 01:10:06,262
the, "Oh, no, not getting
into more trouble, no."

1361
01:10:06,302 --> 01:10:08,668
- (kid screams)
- (woman screams)

1362
01:10:12,575 --> 01:10:15,009
Here, let me cover you up.
(babbling)

1363
01:10:15,044 --> 01:10:19,413
(woman screaming)
Get me out of here!

1364
01:10:19,448 --> 01:10:21,780
(orchestra playing jazz)

1365
01:10:33,429 --> 01:10:35,795
- (orchestra stops)
- (laughter)

1366
01:10:48,043 --> 01:10:50,978
I dug the '60s comic books when I was
a kid. I thought they were great.

1367
01:10:51,013 --> 01:10:53,481
His comic books rocked.

1368
01:10:53,515 --> 01:10:55,574
His comic books were made
better than Bob Hope's.

1369
01:10:55,618 --> 01:10:57,950
I just gotta say that.
I know it's controversial.

1370
01:10:57,987 --> 01:10:59,477
(laughter)

1371
01:10:59,521 --> 01:11:01,648
But Jerry did the better comic
than Bob Hope.

1372
01:11:01,690 --> 01:11:03,715
Jerry Lewis: Oh, Jesus.
- (Tarantino laughing)

1373
01:11:03,759 --> 01:11:05,750
He just spit
on the American flag.

1374
01:11:05,794 --> 01:11:09,321
Tarantino: Well, I remember
one of Truffaut's quotes:

1375
01:11:09,365 --> 01:11:11,128
Jerry Lewis is almost like

1376
01:11:11,166 --> 01:11:13,657
a whole year's worth of cartoons
in one performance.

1377
01:11:26,081 --> 01:11:30,142
Jerry's comedy existed in the world
where cartoons already existed.

1378
01:11:30,185 --> 01:11:32,585
Jerry Lewis is kind of like
a cartoon figure.

1379
01:11:32,621 --> 01:11:34,953
(laughter and applause)

1380
01:11:34,990 --> 01:11:37,288
(cheering)

1381
01:11:43,599 --> 01:11:45,999
He was a kid.
I mean, I loved the cartoon gags.

1382
01:11:49,371 --> 01:11:50,702
Whoa!

1383
01:11:50,739 --> 01:11:53,606
There's real Tex Avery stuff
going on.

1384
01:11:53,642 --> 01:11:55,303
(groans)

1385
01:11:55,344 --> 01:11:56,902
(roars)

1386
01:11:56,945 --> 01:12:00,745
My God, that's just what I did
all the time as a kid...

1387
01:12:00,783 --> 01:12:03,274
you know, making faces.

1388
01:12:03,319 --> 01:12:05,412
There was nobody better at it
than him.

1389
01:12:05,454 --> 01:12:08,321
(giggling)

1390
01:12:10,125 --> 01:12:12,821
(cheering and applause)

1391
01:12:19,968 --> 01:12:22,562
Jerry went back
to the silent era

1392
01:12:22,604 --> 01:12:26,597
and he brought visual sight gags
back to American movie theaters.

1393
01:12:26,642 --> 01:12:28,940
They weren't doing that
for a long time.

1394
01:12:28,977 --> 01:12:32,037
Long before the Zuckers
did "Airplane!"

1395
01:12:32,081 --> 01:12:35,209
Which I think owes a lot
to Jerry Lewis movies,

1396
01:12:35,250 --> 01:12:37,241
and before those great
visual comedies...

1397
01:12:37,286 --> 01:12:40,744
you know, like all
the Leslie Nielsen comedies.

1398
01:12:42,558 --> 01:12:45,994
You have to look at Jerry.
He's kind of the father of that style

1399
01:12:46,028 --> 01:12:47,689
of gags.

1400
01:12:53,502 --> 01:12:55,402
Oh!

1401
01:12:58,440 --> 01:13:00,601
(cheering and applause)

1402
01:13:09,551 --> 01:13:12,952
I've always thought
that there was a connection

1403
01:13:12,988 --> 01:13:15,013
between Jerry Lewis
and Bugs Bunny a little bit,

1404
01:13:15,057 --> 01:13:16,820
but one of the biggest
connections is,

1405
01:13:16,859 --> 01:13:18,986
when Bugs Bunny would get
dressed up as a woman,

1406
01:13:19,027 --> 01:13:21,222
well, that's pretty much like
when Jerry Lewis

1407
01:13:21,263 --> 01:13:23,356
got dressed up
as Carmen Miranda, all right?

1408
01:13:23,399 --> 01:13:25,492
(laughing)
And one of the weird things about it

1409
01:13:25,534 --> 01:13:28,935
is they actually go
for sex appeal.

1410
01:13:28,971 --> 01:13:30,996
He looks like a girl.

1411
01:13:52,861 --> 01:13:57,025
Tarantino: "Looney Tunes" would
constantly break the fourth wall

1412
01:13:57,065 --> 01:13:59,659
and talk to somebody
in the theater...

1413
01:13:59,701 --> 01:14:01,965
"Hey, you in the third row,
shut up."

1414
01:14:02,004 --> 01:14:05,531
Over here.
Let's not fool with the child star.

1415
01:14:05,574 --> 01:14:09,237
Tarantino: The end of "Patsy"
when he falls...

1416
01:14:09,278 --> 01:14:11,439
- Whoa!
- Stanley!

1417
01:14:11,480 --> 01:14:13,914
Tarantino: It's a perfect example
of a "Looney Tunes,"

1418
01:14:13,949 --> 01:14:15,883
break the fourth wall...
this is what we're watching,

1419
01:14:15,918 --> 01:14:17,977
in fact, and why are you
watching it? (laughs)

1420
01:14:18,020 --> 01:14:19,385
Stanley.

1421
01:14:19,421 --> 01:14:22,083
Aren't you overacting a little bit,
Miss Balin? Balin.

1422
01:14:22,124 --> 01:14:24,422
It's a movie, see?
I'm fine.

1423
01:14:24,460 --> 01:14:26,724
The people in the theater know
I ain't gonna die.

1424
01:14:26,762 --> 01:14:29,230
Here, it's a movie stage.
Here, look at this, see?

1425
01:14:29,264 --> 01:14:31,664
There's wires and lights.
And I'm gonna make more movies,

1426
01:14:31,700 --> 01:14:34,760
so I couldn't die. It's like
a make-believe. It's a dumb city.

1427
01:14:34,803 --> 01:14:38,705
Tarantino: That's still kind of
a bizarre joke today. It's out there.

1428
01:14:38,740 --> 01:14:41,174
You are a complete nut.

1429
01:14:41,210 --> 01:14:43,337
Which reminds me, I'm having nuts
and whipped cream for lunch.

1430
01:14:43,378 --> 01:14:45,243
Would you join me, please?
Crew, that's lunch.

1431
01:14:45,280 --> 01:14:47,840
One hour for the actors
and seven days for the technicians.

1432
01:14:47,883 --> 01:14:50,249
It's a movie set
breaking once and for all...

1433
01:14:54,256 --> 01:14:56,554
(wheezing, mutters)

1434
01:14:56,592 --> 01:14:59,186
Jerry Lewis: There's a lot of
resilience in a director.

1435
01:14:59,228 --> 01:15:00,957
He can take a lot of crap.

1436
01:15:00,996 --> 01:15:03,692
It's too heavy.
You'd better cut it, Lenny.

1437
01:15:03,732 --> 01:15:04,892
(crew laughing)

1438
01:15:04,933 --> 01:15:08,733
Jerry Lewis: What he has to exude
for the actors

1439
01:15:08,770 --> 01:15:13,230
is solid confidence
that he knows

1440
01:15:13,275 --> 01:15:15,539
the way you're gonna cut it,

1441
01:15:15,577 --> 01:15:18,102
and the director
is gonna tell you.

1442
01:15:18,146 --> 01:15:20,137
When you make a set-up,

1443
01:15:20,182 --> 01:15:23,151
know where it's coming from,
to there,

1444
01:15:23,185 --> 01:15:25,710
and where that's going,
to there.

1445
01:15:25,754 --> 01:15:28,917
The captain of the National Airlines jet
just flew in from New York

1446
01:15:28,957 --> 01:15:31,425
and he left his briefcase
in the cockpit of the plane.

1447
01:15:31,460 --> 01:15:34,258
- Now get down there and get it.
- (tires screech)

1448
01:15:34,296 --> 01:15:38,426
Jerry Lewis: In "The Bellboy,"
when I had him drive to the airport,

1449
01:15:38,467 --> 01:15:42,233
go into the airport,
walk up the steps,

1450
01:15:42,271 --> 01:15:44,899
he's looking for
the captain's briefcase...

1451
01:15:44,940 --> 01:15:47,602
didn't have to say anything;
didn't have to do anything;

1452
01:15:47,643 --> 01:15:49,941
music wasn't even important.

1453
01:15:54,583 --> 01:15:56,813
Oh, Stanley?
Yes, he works for me.

1454
01:16:00,522 --> 01:16:02,456
He what?

1455
01:16:02,491 --> 01:16:05,289
(engine roaring)

1456
01:16:05,327 --> 01:16:07,955
The fact that it was
on the cut:

1457
01:16:07,996 --> 01:16:10,294
"He what?"
Bang!

1458
01:16:10,332 --> 01:16:13,824
<i>He's up there at 7,000 feet.</i>

1459
01:16:16,071 --> 01:16:18,471
I recut it 13 times,

1460
01:16:18,507 --> 01:16:21,965
always coming back
to the original thought...

1461
01:16:22,010 --> 01:16:25,844
chick-choo, chick-choo,
chick-choo.

1462
01:16:25,881 --> 01:16:28,349
You take a beat
between "chick"...

1463
01:16:28,383 --> 01:16:31,318
you can't do that.

1464
01:16:31,353 --> 01:16:35,016
Man: Would you say something
into the microphone for me?

1465
01:16:35,057 --> 01:16:37,150
- Jerry Lewis: Now?
- Okay.

1466
01:16:40,128 --> 01:16:41,618
(loudly)
How's it going?

1467
01:16:41,663 --> 01:16:43,790
Geronimo!

1468
01:16:45,801 --> 01:16:48,861
Jerry Lewis: The creative mind
needs sound and picture.

1469
01:16:48,904 --> 01:16:51,134
Argh!

1470
01:16:51,173 --> 01:16:53,767
I have to have the sound

1471
01:16:53,809 --> 01:16:57,802
as vitally important
as the picture.

1472
01:16:57,846 --> 01:17:00,178
(footsteps squeaking)

1473
01:17:12,527 --> 01:17:14,893
(footsteps squeaking)

1474
01:17:20,569 --> 01:17:22,696
(school bell rings)

1475
01:17:22,738 --> 01:17:25,036
Jerry Lewis: He comes in.

1476
01:17:25,073 --> 01:17:27,701
We see that he's just blotto.

1477
01:17:27,743 --> 01:17:30,871
It's the hangover
of the century.

1478
01:17:30,912 --> 01:17:34,541
I used the slam
of a safe door.

1479
01:17:34,583 --> 01:17:36,847
(loud bong)

1480
01:17:36,885 --> 01:17:38,250
Oh.

1481
01:17:38,286 --> 01:17:41,414
Jerry Lewis: And I went
to the Bank of America to shoot it.

1482
01:17:41,456 --> 01:17:43,924
And we recorded the...

1483
01:17:43,959 --> 01:17:48,419
bo-o-ong!

1484
01:17:48,463 --> 01:17:51,728
And I had the mike
on the inner door,

1485
01:17:51,767 --> 01:17:55,134
so you really heard
what nobody ever heard.

1486
01:17:55,170 --> 01:17:56,660
(booms)

1487
01:17:56,705 --> 01:17:59,606
No one's ever been in there
when they did that.

1488
01:17:59,641 --> 01:18:01,541
(squeaking)

1489
01:18:01,576 --> 01:18:05,171
Jerry Lewis: Chalk on the board...

1490
01:18:05,213 --> 01:18:07,647
it bothered me watching it.

1491
01:18:07,683 --> 01:18:08,843
Oh.

1492
01:18:08,884 --> 01:18:11,751
(chewing loudly)

1493
01:18:12,754 --> 01:18:14,949
(sneezes)
The sneeze.

1494
01:18:14,990 --> 01:18:17,254
(loud noise)

1495
01:18:17,292 --> 01:18:19,385
Jerry Lewis: I used a grizzly bear's
growl for that.

1496
01:18:19,428 --> 01:18:23,262
(loud hisses)

1497
01:18:23,298 --> 01:18:25,289
(drops echoing)

1498
01:18:25,333 --> 01:18:28,063
I had about 26 sounds.

1499
01:18:29,538 --> 01:18:31,768
A book.

1500
01:18:31,807 --> 01:18:33,035
(loud thud)

1501
01:18:34,042 --> 01:18:38,001
Nobody realizes
how loud a book can be.

1502
01:18:39,014 --> 01:18:41,414
Now you enlarge that sound.

1503
01:18:44,219 --> 01:18:46,210
No, it's better with a hardcover.

1504
01:18:46,254 --> 01:18:48,745
It's better with a hardcover.

1505
01:18:48,790 --> 01:18:50,087
(piano intro plays)

1506
01:18:50,125 --> 01:18:51,285
(horn blows)

1507
01:18:51,326 --> 01:18:53,726
(laughter and cheering)

1508
01:19:00,235 --> 01:19:03,762
Is someone
giving birth back there?

1509
01:19:03,805 --> 01:19:05,796
Name it after me.

1510
01:19:05,841 --> 01:19:08,309
These are the glasses

1511
01:19:08,343 --> 01:19:11,039
that we are seriously
contemplating using

1512
01:19:11,079 --> 01:19:13,707
for some of the sequences.

1513
01:19:13,749 --> 01:19:15,740
Let me try
the other ones now.

1514
01:19:17,419 --> 01:19:20,445
Oh, God, that pinches.

1515
01:19:20,489 --> 01:19:23,549
Profile smile... to see
that the teeth are correct.

1516
01:19:23,592 --> 01:19:24,854
(man laughs)

1517
01:19:24,893 --> 01:19:27,259
This is the makeup

1518
01:19:27,295 --> 01:19:30,230
with a little more red.

1519
01:19:30,265 --> 01:19:33,496
Murphy: I do get to stretch more
when I put stuff on,

1520
01:19:33,535 --> 01:19:35,935
because you have
whatever your baggage is

1521
01:19:35,971 --> 01:19:38,462
when you show up,
and your little stuff

1522
01:19:38,507 --> 01:19:40,441
that people expect of you.

1523
01:19:40,475 --> 01:19:43,137
When you're somebody else,
they don't know what to expect.

1524
01:19:43,178 --> 01:19:45,237
You get to do a lot
of different things.

1525
01:19:45,280 --> 01:19:48,181
And Jerry did that, you know,
before anybody as well.

1526
01:19:48,216 --> 01:19:51,049
Hello, Los Angeles tower.
This is Eddie's Airways,

1527
01:19:51,086 --> 01:19:53,987
the airline for the birds.
Ha-ha-ha! A little pun.

1528
01:19:57,492 --> 01:20:00,518
Chase: I think of him put in a situation

1529
01:20:00,562 --> 01:20:02,962
the way you put Peter Sellers
into a situation,

1530
01:20:02,998 --> 01:20:06,695
and he turns and he's got
this stuff on his nose.

1531
01:20:06,735 --> 01:20:09,067
Don't tell me that
that hadn't occurred to Jerry

1532
01:20:09,104 --> 01:20:10,696
a few years earlier.
(laughs)

1533
01:20:10,739 --> 01:20:13,037
Battle stations!

1534
01:20:13,074 --> 01:20:14,701
(ringing bells)

1535
01:20:14,743 --> 01:20:16,802
Murphy:
Peter Sellers gets credited

1536
01:20:16,845 --> 01:20:18,870
with doing stuff like that.

1537
01:20:18,914 --> 01:20:21,109
Jerry's doing it
before everybody's doing

1538
01:20:21,149 --> 01:20:23,140
multiple character stuff.

1539
01:20:24,686 --> 01:20:28,520
Chase:
This guy... me, Fletch,

1540
01:20:28,557 --> 01:20:31,287
using multiple funny costumes
that I wore...

1541
01:20:31,326 --> 01:20:35,057
if it in any way rang of Jerry Lewis,
I'm proud of it.

1542
01:20:35,096 --> 01:20:38,088
- Man: Your name, sir.
- Uh, Bugs Peyton.

1543
01:20:38,133 --> 01:20:39,623
What is it again?

1544
01:20:39,668 --> 01:20:42,899
I said Bugs Peyton.
My name... Bugs Peyton.

1545
01:20:42,938 --> 01:20:44,530
Mugs Peyton?

1546
01:20:44,573 --> 01:20:46,871
Hey, schmuck,
Bugs, not Mugs.

1547
01:20:46,908 --> 01:20:49,274
What's this there?
A television?

1548
01:20:49,311 --> 01:20:50,801
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

1549
01:20:50,846 --> 01:20:53,110
- What business are you in?
- I'm a priest.

1550
01:20:53,148 --> 01:20:56,174
(crew laughing)

1551
01:20:56,218 --> 01:20:58,880
Man:
You're a priest?

1552
01:20:58,920 --> 01:21:03,448
Yeah, free rites at the Mormon
Tabernacle Temple in Idaho.

1553
01:21:03,491 --> 01:21:05,982
Man:
You look Jewish to me.

1554
01:21:06,027 --> 01:21:08,930
- Doesn't everybody?
- (laughter)

1555
01:21:08,930 --> 01:21:11,490
I really think

1556
01:21:11,533 --> 01:21:14,969
Jerry should get
a Kennedy Center honor.

1557
01:21:15,003 --> 01:21:17,563
Jerry Lewis:
Jack came out of the service

1558
01:21:17,606 --> 01:21:20,939
when Dean and I were playing
the Chez Paree in Chicago.

1559
01:21:20,976 --> 01:21:24,070
And we lived
at the Ambassador East.

1560
01:21:24,112 --> 01:21:26,103
I had a suite on the north side

1561
01:21:26,147 --> 01:21:28,581
and Jack's suite
was on the south side.

1562
01:21:28,617 --> 01:21:30,881
And he would come in to me
every once in a while

1563
01:21:30,919 --> 01:21:35,083
and asked me what I thought
of this paragraph, and he reads it.

1564
01:21:35,123 --> 01:21:38,149
And about the third time he came in
with something, I said,

1565
01:21:38,193 --> 01:21:42,061
"Are you doing a speech?
Are you appearing somewhere?"

1566
01:21:42,097 --> 01:21:44,190
He said, "No, this is something else.

1567
01:21:44,232 --> 01:21:46,564
I'm calling it 'Profiles in Courage."'

1568
01:21:46,601 --> 01:21:48,660
I said, "Really?"

1569
01:21:48,703 --> 01:21:52,605
The book that became my bible.

1570
01:21:52,641 --> 01:21:56,577
I'd give my soul if I could have dinner
with Jack Kennedy again.

1571
01:21:56,611 --> 01:21:59,205
He never ever spent time with me

1572
01:21:59,247 --> 01:22:03,911
that I didn't hear something
I never wanted to forget.

1573
01:22:03,952 --> 01:22:08,252
One day we were in Hyannis Port

1574
01:22:08,290 --> 01:22:10,451
and we're on the golf course.

1575
01:22:10,492 --> 01:22:14,485
And the one thing that
Jack Kennedy told me for sure...

1576
01:22:14,529 --> 01:22:18,226
"Don't get into
anything political.

1577
01:22:18,266 --> 01:22:20,257
You're gonna lose
half your audience."

1578
01:22:21,970 --> 01:22:24,530
Whenever I came to see
Jack Kennedy,

1579
01:22:24,572 --> 01:22:27,905
he made sure I came up through
the bowels of the White House,

1580
01:22:27,943 --> 01:22:31,435
up through the staircase
and into the Oval Office,

1581
01:22:31,479 --> 01:22:33,743
so that the press didn't ever know
I was with him.

1582
01:22:33,782 --> 01:22:35,773
I had 19 visits

1583
01:22:35,817 --> 01:22:38,479
and no one ever knew it.

1584
01:22:40,188 --> 01:22:43,555
I did his last birthday appearance.

1585
01:22:43,591 --> 01:22:46,560
It was the night of his birthday
at the Armory

1586
01:22:46,594 --> 01:22:48,994
and I was teasing Jack.

1587
01:22:49,030 --> 01:22:52,158
(onstage) Could you put the light on
so I can see if he's here?

1588
01:22:52,200 --> 01:22:55,169
Mr. Pres... would you just wave
so I know?

1589
01:22:55,203 --> 01:22:57,103
Is he here?

1590
01:22:57,138 --> 01:22:59,698
Because if you got me here
all the way for nothing...

1591
01:22:59,741 --> 01:23:02,335
Is that you?

1592
01:23:02,377 --> 01:23:05,175
Mr. President,
it's me... Jerry.

1593
01:23:05,213 --> 01:23:08,205
Remember? The nut.
I voted for you.

1594
01:23:08,249 --> 01:23:11,150
(narrating) I'll never forget it,
as long as I live.

1595
01:23:17,325 --> 01:23:21,056
Seinfeld: There is no real
low-brow in comedy.

1596
01:23:21,096 --> 01:23:24,031
(tires screech)

1597
01:23:24,065 --> 01:23:26,260
It's even harder to do that

1598
01:23:26,301 --> 01:23:28,292
than some other forms
of comedy

1599
01:23:28,336 --> 01:23:30,600
where you have
dialogue and character.

1600
01:23:30,638 --> 01:23:33,232
Just get in a car
and make me laugh.

1601
01:23:33,274 --> 01:23:35,139
(humming a tune)

1602
01:23:35,176 --> 01:23:37,007
(Seinfeld chuckling)
That is not easy.

1603
01:23:37,045 --> 01:23:39,036
(woman over speaker)
Fella!

1604
01:23:39,080 --> 01:23:40,980
Yes, Stepmother.

1605
01:23:41,016 --> 01:23:42,813
Stepmother:
Where's my car?

1606
01:23:42,851 --> 01:23:44,716
Seinfeld:
To drive a Rolls Royce

1607
01:23:44,753 --> 01:23:48,587
and to make the car funny,

1608
01:23:48,623 --> 01:23:50,955
to drive funny...

1609
01:23:50,992 --> 01:23:54,450
no one else
has ever done this.

1610
01:23:54,496 --> 01:23:56,521
This is brilliant.

1611
01:23:56,564 --> 01:23:59,897
This is sophisticated.

1612
01:23:59,934 --> 01:24:02,459
You gotta be a genius
to figure out

1613
01:24:02,504 --> 01:24:05,871
how to make a car
drive funny,

1614
01:24:05,907 --> 01:24:08,671
so that you watch the car
and you laugh at the car.

1615
01:24:08,710 --> 01:24:11,440
Enjoy your ride, Stepmother.
I fixed the car

1616
01:24:11,479 --> 01:24:13,640
perfectly mechanically
beautifully.

1617
01:24:13,681 --> 01:24:14,909
(wheezes)

1618
01:24:14,949 --> 01:24:17,281
Seinfeld: This is not
lowbrow to me.

1619
01:24:17,318 --> 01:24:19,309
This is the highest brow.

1620
01:24:19,354 --> 01:24:23,518
Jerry Lewis, Noel Coward...
you know, right there.

1621
01:24:23,558 --> 01:24:26,425
(car creaking)

1622
01:24:26,461 --> 01:24:29,123
- My name is Bettina Bailey.
- What is it?

1623
01:24:29,164 --> 01:24:31,064
- Bettina.
- Bettina?

1624
01:24:31,099 --> 01:24:33,090
- Bettina, yes.
- That's so nice.

1625
01:24:33,134 --> 01:24:36,365
Um, I want to let you know

1626
01:24:36,404 --> 01:24:40,135
my lifelong dream,
if you wouldn't mind,

1627
01:24:40,175 --> 01:24:42,803
to hug you, please.

1628
01:24:44,546 --> 01:24:45,740
Here?

1629
01:24:45,780 --> 01:24:48,305
(laughter)

1630
01:24:48,349 --> 01:24:50,579
Now?

1631
01:24:50,618 --> 01:24:53,678
Or if you got a room back there,
you know, either way.

1632
01:24:53,721 --> 01:24:56,485
(laughter)

1633
01:24:56,524 --> 01:24:59,516
It's so nice of you.
I'll tell you what:

1634
01:24:59,561 --> 01:25:02,496
After the show,
if you come backstage,

1635
01:25:02,530 --> 01:25:05,363
I will let security know
to let you in.

1636
01:25:05,400 --> 01:25:07,834
I will give you a hug,
but I cannot promise you

1637
01:25:07,869 --> 01:25:10,394
that it'll end there.

1638
01:25:13,374 --> 01:25:16,309
Woman:
On Myspace, they asked,

1639
01:25:16,344 --> 01:25:17,868
"Who would you most like
to meet?"

1640
01:25:17,912 --> 01:25:19,903
Well, my number one was God,

1641
01:25:19,948 --> 01:25:22,280
- but my number two was you.
- (crowd exclaims)

1642
01:25:22,317 --> 01:25:25,150
So maybe we can make it
a threesome with Bettina

1643
01:25:25,186 --> 01:25:28,678
- and let me come back, get a hug?
- (laughter and cheering)

1644
01:25:32,927 --> 01:25:35,395
I'm gonna be busy, ain't I?

1645
01:25:35,430 --> 01:25:38,866
Is the drug store open?

1646
01:25:38,900 --> 01:25:41,664
You don't need it.
I've gone through menopause.

1647
01:25:41,703 --> 01:25:43,967
- Oh, Jesus.
- (cheering and applause)

1648
01:25:50,778 --> 01:25:53,042
One, two, three, four...

1649
01:26:29,517 --> 01:26:32,315
What I do when I dance is fake.

1650
01:26:32,353 --> 01:26:34,583
(laughs)

1651
01:26:34,622 --> 01:26:37,750
I am one of the faking fools.

1652
01:26:37,792 --> 01:26:40,056
The dancing became

1653
01:26:40,094 --> 01:26:42,085
a part of the writing process.

1654
01:26:42,130 --> 01:26:44,121
(swing music playing)

1655
01:26:44,165 --> 01:26:46,156
What I love about Jerry is,

1656
01:26:46,201 --> 01:26:48,897
he's never had a dance lesson
in his life, he told me.

1657
01:26:48,937 --> 01:26:52,771
He fakes it. Well, goodness me,
he fakes better than I dance.

1658
01:26:52,807 --> 01:26:55,105
(swing music continues)

1659
01:27:39,053 --> 01:27:41,453
I know nothing about dancing

1660
01:27:41,489 --> 01:27:44,515
other than time, rhythm.

1661
01:27:44,559 --> 01:27:47,653
I stood in the wings
watching my dad

1662
01:27:47,695 --> 01:27:51,859
at the ripe age...
five, six, seven, eight.

1663
01:27:51,899 --> 01:27:56,131
I mean, I watched some of the best
dancers in the world.

1664
01:27:58,172 --> 01:28:00,970
He was trying
to experiment with comedy

1665
01:28:01,009 --> 01:28:04,740
in a weird way that Gene Kelly
was trying to experiment

1666
01:28:04,779 --> 01:28:06,838
with what you could do
with dance in movies.

1667
01:28:06,881 --> 01:28:09,850
(fanfare)

1668
01:28:09,884 --> 01:28:13,547
(percussion intro plays)

1669
01:28:13,588 --> 01:28:16,182
(jazz orchestra playing)

1670
01:28:16,224 --> 01:28:18,658
Jerry Lewis:
I gave the crew the setup.

1671
01:28:18,693 --> 01:28:21,890
I had tracks.
Music was ready.

1672
01:28:21,929 --> 01:28:24,693
And I had to be ready.
When I was ready, I went.

1673
01:28:59,434 --> 01:29:01,493
That was my own
choreography.

1674
01:29:01,536 --> 01:29:03,731
I did that in take one.

1675
01:29:03,771 --> 01:29:06,797
Two setups...
I did the whole dance.

1676
01:29:06,841 --> 01:29:08,468
The front office was
in shock

1677
01:29:08,509 --> 01:29:10,909
because I shot that whole sequence
in four hours.

1678
01:29:29,297 --> 01:29:31,788
I went up the stairs
in eight seconds.

1679
01:29:31,833 --> 01:29:34,996
- (clock chimes)
- I think I'll have to get along.

1680
01:29:35,036 --> 01:29:37,027
I'll never forget you.

1681
01:29:43,177 --> 01:29:47,170
Jerry Lewis: 66 steps
in eight seconds.

1682
01:29:47,215 --> 01:29:50,912
But at the top of the steps
I had a heart failure.

1683
01:29:52,220 --> 01:29:56,156
I was in Mount Sinai Hospital

1684
01:29:56,190 --> 01:29:58,090
30 minutes later.

1685
01:29:58,126 --> 01:30:01,061
The insurance company
didn't want to pay us.

1686
01:30:01,095 --> 01:30:03,256
They didn't believe I made it
in eight seconds.

1687
01:30:03,297 --> 01:30:05,322
And they kept looking
at the film.

1688
01:30:05,366 --> 01:30:07,357
I said, "The film don't lie."

1689
01:30:07,402 --> 01:30:10,633
66 steps in eight seconds.
(chuckles)

1690
01:30:14,142 --> 01:30:18,135
While I'm in the oxygen tent,
my father opens the flap,

1691
01:30:18,179 --> 01:30:21,046
looks in and says, "Do you know
what you're doing to your mother?"

1692
01:30:21,082 --> 01:30:22,447
My baby.

1693
01:30:22,483 --> 01:30:24,974
I'm lying here,
hoping I'm gonna survive,

1694
01:30:25,019 --> 01:30:27,886
and he's asking me if I know
what I'm doing to my mother.

1695
01:30:27,922 --> 01:30:29,890
It was a perfect Jewish question.

1696
01:30:29,924 --> 01:30:32,392
Oh, my child.

1697
01:30:32,427 --> 01:30:34,861
(laughter)

1698
01:30:34,896 --> 01:30:38,229
Seinfeld: He's a brilliant
musician of comedy.

1699
01:30:38,266 --> 01:30:40,530
Comedy is math and music.

1700
01:30:40,568 --> 01:30:43,093
It's very precise
and mathematical,

1701
01:30:43,137 --> 01:30:47,904
but it has to have
a musical kind of flow to it.

1702
01:30:47,942 --> 01:30:50,137
(playing fanfare intro)

1703
01:30:57,852 --> 01:31:00,286
Maybe it could be
just a touch faster.

1704
01:31:00,321 --> 01:31:02,152
Okay? Same thing. Thanks.

1705
01:31:02,190 --> 01:31:04,988
If you waved your arms faster,
it would have been faster.

1706
01:31:05,026 --> 01:31:07,392
(musicians laughing)

1707
01:31:08,396 --> 01:31:11,957
They played exactly
what you were doing.

1708
01:31:11,999 --> 01:31:16,436
Belzer: I watched JL
rehearse a 36-piece orchestra

1709
01:31:16,471 --> 01:31:18,462
and know every instrument.

1710
01:31:18,506 --> 01:31:22,135
I mean, this is a musical genius
in the true sense.

1711
01:31:26,481 --> 01:31:28,472
(orchestra stops playing)

1712
01:31:28,516 --> 01:31:31,314
Train wreck.

1713
01:31:31,352 --> 01:31:33,286
(laughter)

1714
01:31:33,321 --> 01:31:37,417
- Rick, where did that happen?
- We've got it covered.

1715
01:31:37,458 --> 01:31:39,358
(laughing)

1716
01:31:39,393 --> 01:31:41,827
Jerry Lewis: When you get music
in your soul

1717
01:31:41,863 --> 01:31:45,629
and you are then becoming
a creative artist...

1718
01:31:45,666 --> 01:31:48,965
I could never just
put music over there.

1719
01:31:49,003 --> 01:31:52,029
It was always imbued
in my being.

1720
01:31:52,073 --> 01:31:55,133
If you look at a scene I did
in "The Patsy,"

1721
01:31:55,176 --> 01:31:58,304
I do the kid that has tickets
for the premiere

1722
01:31:58,346 --> 01:32:00,246
but he's not dressed for it.

1723
01:32:00,281 --> 01:32:02,875
I chewed that scene
for four days

1724
01:32:02,917 --> 01:32:07,581
till I got it exactly
the way I wanted it.

1725
01:32:07,622 --> 01:32:10,420
And then, when I scored it,

1726
01:32:10,458 --> 01:32:13,621
I still didn't get it perfect.

1727
01:32:13,661 --> 01:32:17,791
And then I took one of the pieces
of music that we had recorded

1728
01:32:17,832 --> 01:32:20,266
and I Mickey-Moused it

1729
01:32:20,301 --> 01:32:24,465
to go...
(imitates sped-up music)

1730
01:32:24,505 --> 01:32:26,905
And it was one spot
where it needed it.

1731
01:32:26,941 --> 01:32:30,843
And it made it happen
really, really good.

1732
01:32:30,878 --> 01:32:34,143
I was very proud of the work.

1733
01:32:37,285 --> 01:32:39,515
You know, you put a comic
on the screen

1734
01:32:39,554 --> 01:32:41,715
for an audience
for eight minutes...

1735
01:32:41,756 --> 01:32:43,656
that's almost a reel.

1736
01:32:43,691 --> 01:32:45,386
(music slows down)

1737
01:32:45,426 --> 01:32:49,328
Without the music it would have been
a whole, long eight minutes.

1738
01:32:49,363 --> 01:32:51,490
The music moved it.

1739
01:32:51,532 --> 01:32:53,523
It gave it that thing

1740
01:32:53,568 --> 01:32:58,005
that an audience sitting
in the theater needs to be told.

1741
01:32:58,039 --> 01:33:00,303
- (music vamping)
- Pull the tracks out of there

1742
01:33:00,341 --> 01:33:03,037
and look at it,
and it almost works without it.

1743
01:33:03,077 --> 01:33:05,671
But it will never work
with wrong music.

1744
01:33:11,419 --> 01:33:15,082
When you talk of comedy
as the art form,

1745
01:33:15,122 --> 01:33:18,683
it demands
what music gives it.

1746
01:33:23,364 --> 01:33:25,355
The trombone will play D-flat,

1747
01:33:25,399 --> 01:33:29,836
you play E,
and you play E-sharp, okay?

1748
01:33:29,870 --> 01:33:32,498
Listen to this, folks.

1749
01:33:32,540 --> 01:33:37,000
(dissonant chord plays)

1750
01:33:37,044 --> 01:33:40,241
Man:
That is the shit.

1751
01:33:40,281 --> 01:33:42,340
There's always one
that don't belong there,

1752
01:33:42,383 --> 01:33:44,374
but if it was out of there,
it'd be perfect.

1753
01:33:44,418 --> 01:33:46,249
(laughter)

1754
01:33:46,287 --> 01:33:48,517
- Thanks, Jerry.
- Okay.

1755
01:33:50,958 --> 01:33:52,755
Good night,
ladies and gentlemen.

1756
01:33:52,793 --> 01:33:54,454
- Do we have a gentleman?
- No.

1757
01:33:54,495 --> 01:33:57,828
Good. Screw them.

1758
01:33:57,865 --> 01:33:59,730
Cough.

1759
01:34:02,203 --> 01:34:04,569
When you have a guy
in the band

1760
01:34:04,605 --> 01:34:07,403
who's better than everybody else
at his instrument,

1761
01:34:07,441 --> 01:34:09,272
you gotta hear a solo.

1762
01:34:09,310 --> 01:34:12,245
(humming a tune)

1763
01:34:12,279 --> 01:34:14,873
And the same with Jerry...
you know, you want to see Jerry

1764
01:34:14,915 --> 01:34:18,510
in a funny movie, and then you want
to see him just do a solo,

1765
01:34:18,552 --> 01:34:20,486
'cause he's that good.

1766
01:34:20,521 --> 01:34:23,456
(orchestra playing jazz)

1767
01:34:49,817 --> 01:34:52,047
(trombone solo playing)

1768
01:35:04,598 --> 01:35:06,395
(trumpet solo playing)

1769
01:35:11,939 --> 01:35:13,531
(music finishes)

1770
01:35:13,574 --> 01:35:17,344
I did take one... print it.

1771
01:35:17,344 --> 01:35:19,312
See what happened

1772
01:35:19,346 --> 01:35:23,305
<i>September the 4th, 1976,</i>

1773
01:35:23,350 --> 01:35:26,251
that created the most talk

1774
01:35:26,287 --> 01:35:27,982
in the world of television.

1775
01:35:28,022 --> 01:35:29,421
(studio applause)

1776
01:35:29,457 --> 01:35:32,654
I have a friend who loves
what you do every year.

1777
01:35:32,693 --> 01:35:35,719
Arthur Forrest: This is quite a story
that almost nobody knows.

1778
01:35:35,763 --> 01:35:38,129
<i>It was 1976.</i>

1779
01:35:38,165 --> 01:35:40,793
And the phone rang.
It's Frank Sinatra.

1780
01:35:40,835 --> 01:35:43,269
He said, "If I was to bring Dean
on the show,

1781
01:35:43,304 --> 01:35:45,067
how do you think
he'd react?"

1782
01:35:45,106 --> 01:35:48,701
And I said, "I think he would
react marvelously."

1783
01:35:48,743 --> 01:35:51,234
And they hadn't really
reconciled yet.

1784
01:35:51,278 --> 01:35:54,509
Forrest: And he says, "I've arranged it.
He wants to do the show."

1785
01:35:54,548 --> 01:35:57,016
We didn't tell anybody
because we knew

1786
01:35:57,051 --> 01:35:59,417
if it leaked out,
I would be a dead man.

1787
01:35:59,453 --> 01:36:03,014
They said, "He'd come up
in a limo with seven or eight people

1788
01:36:03,057 --> 01:36:06,549
and Dean would be one of them
with a raincoat and a hat and glasses."

1789
01:36:06,594 --> 01:36:10,621
I said, "When Frank comes out,
make sure all the stations down the line

1790
01:36:10,664 --> 01:36:12,154
record his appearance.

1791
01:36:12,199 --> 01:36:14,667
Get all the PR people you can
in the audience.

1792
01:36:14,702 --> 01:36:16,795
It's gonna be a big story."
They said, "What is it?"

1793
01:36:16,837 --> 01:36:18,498
I said, "I can't tell you,
but just trust me."

1794
01:36:18,539 --> 01:36:20,404
Sinatra: Just tell him out there
to come in.

1795
01:36:20,441 --> 01:36:23,672
(cheering and applause)

1796
01:36:23,711 --> 01:36:27,704
Jerry Lewis: We would meet
for the first time in 20 years

1797
01:36:27,748 --> 01:36:29,739
only because of the stupidity

1798
01:36:29,784 --> 01:36:32,651
of when people
get highly emotional.

1799
01:36:32,686 --> 01:36:35,553
And we both felt badly
about that.

1800
01:36:37,424 --> 01:36:39,915
And I'm looking,
and I went,

1801
01:36:39,960 --> 01:36:42,451
"Oh my gosh,
that's Dad walking out,"

1802
01:36:42,496 --> 01:36:44,487
'cause I could tell his walk.

1803
01:36:44,532 --> 01:36:47,330
And then when I saw his face
and I saw Jerry's face

1804
01:36:47,368 --> 01:36:49,700
and they hugged...

1805
01:36:52,406 --> 01:36:56,035
<i>Chris Lewis: That scream that came out
of that audience of 750 people...</i>

1806
01:36:56,076 --> 01:36:58,510
<i>I mean, it sounded like
750,000 people.</i>

1807
01:36:58,546 --> 01:37:00,810
It was just amazing.

1808
01:37:03,617 --> 01:37:07,644
Jerry Lewis: People love to know
that love prevails.

1809
01:37:07,688 --> 01:37:09,622
So how have you been?

1810
01:37:09,657 --> 01:37:11,648
(laughter)

1811
01:37:12,660 --> 01:37:14,924
Jerry Lewis:
And they went their separate ways.

1812
01:37:14,962 --> 01:37:17,430
They didn't see one another.
And then they got back.

1813
01:37:17,464 --> 01:37:19,864
And when they kissed and hugged
at that last moment,

1814
01:37:19,900 --> 01:37:21,060
it was worth all of that.

1815
01:37:21,101 --> 01:37:23,433
We haven't seen each other
for 20 years.

1816
01:37:23,470 --> 01:37:24,732
(laughs) Yeah.

1817
01:37:24,772 --> 01:37:27,332
Well, you know, there was all those
rumors about our breaking up,

1818
01:37:27,374 --> 01:37:30,366
and then when I started the show
and you weren't here, I believed it.

1819
01:37:30,411 --> 01:37:34,177
Everybody was just dumbfounded.
There wasn't a dry eye in the house.

1820
01:37:34,215 --> 01:37:36,206
So you're working?

1821
01:37:36,250 --> 01:37:38,912
(laughter and applause)

1822
01:37:41,155 --> 01:37:42,782
I love your movies.

1823
01:37:42,823 --> 01:37:45,553
You're, like, the only thing
my parents and I can agree on.

1824
01:37:45,593 --> 01:37:47,493
What did you think
of the Eddie Murphy movie...

1825
01:37:47,528 --> 01:37:49,223
"The Nutty Professor" movie?

1826
01:37:49,263 --> 01:37:51,197
I produced it.
What do you think I thought of it?

1827
01:37:51,232 --> 01:37:54,099
After you cashed the check,
what did you think of it?

1828
01:37:54,134 --> 01:37:58,833
It was my financial pleasure,
I guarantee you.

1829
01:37:58,873 --> 01:38:01,273
(laughs)

1830
01:38:01,308 --> 01:38:04,471
As a filmmaker,
I've been inspired by Jerry.

1831
01:38:04,511 --> 01:38:07,674
And one of my favorite movies
of all time

1832
01:38:07,715 --> 01:38:09,307
growing up
was "The Nutty Professor."

1833
01:38:09,350 --> 01:38:10,977
When I got the chance
to do that again,

1834
01:38:11,018 --> 01:38:13,748
that was like,
"This has to be incredible."

1835
01:38:13,787 --> 01:38:15,880
Because of my love for this man,
this artist,

1836
01:38:15,923 --> 01:38:19,757
it was like, "There's no way we'll do
this movie and not, you know, crush it."

1837
01:38:19,793 --> 01:38:22,591
He was able to look
at Jekyll and Hyde

1838
01:38:22,630 --> 01:38:25,121
and see that,
hey, that's funny

1839
01:38:25,165 --> 01:38:27,929
that you could be this double life
and all that whole stuff.

1840
01:38:27,968 --> 01:38:30,835
That's what's really brilliant
about "The Nutty Professor."

1841
01:38:33,374 --> 01:38:35,365
John Landis: I thought
Eddie was extraordinary.

1842
01:38:35,409 --> 01:38:37,536
I thought his character
as Sherman Klump

1843
01:38:37,578 --> 01:38:40,138
was an absolutely extraordinary
character, and sweet.

1844
01:38:40,180 --> 01:38:42,740
Murphy: That's another thing
that's pioneered by Jerry...

1845
01:38:42,783 --> 01:38:44,774
mixing sweet and funny.

1846
01:38:44,818 --> 01:38:47,309
You don't see that
until Jerry Lewis.

1847
01:38:47,354 --> 01:38:49,185
You see funny

1848
01:38:49,223 --> 01:38:51,817
and you see madcap
and you see slapstick,

1849
01:38:51,859 --> 01:38:55,522
but a character really
sweet and funny... that's Jerry.

1850
01:39:15,015 --> 01:39:17,711
You can't do comedy
unless you know drama.

1851
01:39:17,751 --> 01:39:20,219
I mean, comedy is...

1852
01:39:20,254 --> 01:39:23,587
is the satire of reality.

1853
01:39:23,624 --> 01:39:27,390
And you can't be funny
unless you know what the reality is.

1854
01:39:27,428 --> 01:39:29,589
He mastered that very early.

1855
01:39:29,630 --> 01:39:31,621
You may not believe this,

1856
01:39:31,665 --> 01:39:34,566
but I was a very homely child.

1857
01:39:34,601 --> 01:39:36,592
(laughter)

1858
01:39:36,637 --> 01:39:38,901
Burnett: He was amazing...
amazing to work with.

1859
01:39:38,939 --> 01:39:41,499
Really?

1860
01:39:41,542 --> 01:39:45,842
Yes. My father suggested
plastic surgery.

1861
01:39:45,879 --> 01:39:48,439
Oh, yeah?
When are you gonna have it?

1862
01:39:48,482 --> 01:39:52,350
(laughs)

1863
01:39:53,354 --> 01:39:56,050
I had it already.

1864
01:39:57,091 --> 01:40:00,720
They did a very unusual job.

1865
01:40:00,761 --> 01:40:03,355
Burnett: A lot of clowns
can do straight stuff.

1866
01:40:03,397 --> 01:40:05,524
I loved him
in "King of Comedy."

1867
01:40:05,566 --> 01:40:08,729
You go that far out...
it's easier to bring it back in.

1868
01:40:08,769 --> 01:40:10,794
(crowd clamoring)
Jerry! Jerry!

1869
01:40:10,838 --> 01:40:13,466
Jerry Lewis: I am fortunate
I crossed over

1870
01:40:13,507 --> 01:40:16,635
as strongly as you can
in "The King of Comedy."

1871
01:40:16,677 --> 01:40:21,614
If you are equipped
to do physical, wild craziness

1872
01:40:21,648 --> 01:40:23,445
as I have and do...

1873
01:40:23,484 --> 01:40:25,475
I love... argh!

1874
01:40:28,122 --> 01:40:29,111
Oh, l...

1875
01:40:29,156 --> 01:40:32,717
...with it comes
an authoritative figure

1876
01:40:32,760 --> 01:40:34,751
that comes from down deep

1877
01:40:34,795 --> 01:40:39,164
that can now play it
as dramatically as you please.

1878
01:40:39,199 --> 01:40:42,225
The pressure, the ratings,

1879
01:40:42,269 --> 01:40:45,500
the same guests,
the same questions...

1880
01:40:45,539 --> 01:40:48,099
I'm just not enjoying it
anymore.

1881
01:40:48,142 --> 01:40:52,101
I got more critical acclaim
from that film

1882
01:40:52,146 --> 01:40:55,411
that I did for any of the work
that I did in my whole life.

1883
01:40:55,449 --> 01:40:58,179
Critics acclaiming, acclaiming,
"Oh, he was this,"

1884
01:40:58,218 --> 01:41:00,846
and I'm thinking to myself,
"You schmuck,

1885
01:41:00,888 --> 01:41:04,585
do you realize I showed up and
I just read the words and went home?"

1886
01:41:04,625 --> 01:41:08,026
I mean, I didn't have to do anything.
I had to be me.

1887
01:41:08,062 --> 01:41:10,053
Crystal: Maybe the best
performance he gave

1888
01:41:10,097 --> 01:41:12,759
was "King of Comedy,"
you know, as a serious actor.

1889
01:41:12,800 --> 01:41:15,030
That was harnessing him
in a different way.

1890
01:41:15,069 --> 01:41:16,559
That was another side
of Jerry.

1891
01:41:16,603 --> 01:41:19,231
Oh, he was great in it.
And he embraced who he was.

1892
01:41:19,273 --> 01:41:21,434
And he... you know,

1893
01:41:21,475 --> 01:41:24,103
it wasn't the Jerry that we knew.
He was a different guy.

1894
01:41:24,144 --> 01:41:27,113
You listen to my stuff for 15 minutes,
that's all. Is that asking too much?

1895
01:41:27,147 --> 01:41:29,411
Yes, it is.
I have a life, okay?

1896
01:41:29,450 --> 01:41:32,681
- Well, I have a life too.
- That's not my responsibility.

1897
01:41:32,719 --> 01:41:34,710
Well, it is when you tell me
to call you and then you don't...

1898
01:41:34,755 --> 01:41:37,155
I told you to call
to get rid of you.

1899
01:41:37,191 --> 01:41:40,854
In the Scorsese film
he's more of a leading man

1900
01:41:40,894 --> 01:41:43,454
than he ever was in any film,
and he was older.

1901
01:41:43,497 --> 01:41:45,488
This is a leading man?

1902
01:41:45,532 --> 01:41:47,727
Well, actually I was just
mixing these

1903
01:41:47,768 --> 01:41:50,259
so that we could try
using it on the skin.

1904
01:41:50,304 --> 01:41:53,034
You wonder, what kind of career
would Lewis have had

1905
01:41:53,073 --> 01:41:56,065
if he decided
he wanted to play

1906
01:41:56,110 --> 01:41:59,136
really kind of straightforward,
good-looking leading man.

1907
01:41:59,179 --> 01:42:01,170
Lewis could have done that.

1908
01:42:01,215 --> 01:42:03,740
- (applause)
- You're very wise.

1909
01:42:03,784 --> 01:42:05,775
(laughter)

1910
01:42:05,819 --> 01:42:08,788
Now if you'll just hold it a second,
I'll thrill you some more.

1911
01:42:08,822 --> 01:42:11,347
Seinfeld: He came up with
the character of Buddy Love.

1912
01:42:11,391 --> 01:42:13,916
He wanted to take
the worst qualities

1913
01:42:13,961 --> 01:42:16,259
of the worst people
he had ever met

1914
01:42:16,296 --> 01:42:21,063
and make them into this
very unsympathetic character.

1915
01:42:21,101 --> 01:42:24,730
You rude, discourteous
egomaniac.

1916
01:42:24,771 --> 01:42:27,467
You're crazy about me, right?
And I can understand it.

1917
01:42:27,508 --> 01:42:29,999
Only this morning,
looking in the mirror before shaving,

1918
01:42:30,043 --> 01:42:33,672
I enjoyed seeing what I saw so much,
I couldn't tear myself away.

1919
01:42:33,714 --> 01:42:35,841
(kisses)
Have some, baby?

1920
01:42:35,883 --> 01:42:37,874
Seinfeld: And he was
shocked to find

1921
01:42:37,918 --> 01:42:40,887
that a lot of young people
loved Buddy Love.

1922
01:42:40,921 --> 01:42:44,516
Thank you, kiddies. You're all
very, very nice little boys and girls.

1923
01:42:44,558 --> 01:42:47,391
Seinfeld:
Jerry is incapable

1924
01:42:47,427 --> 01:42:51,488
of not putting love

1925
01:42:51,532 --> 01:42:53,523
into everything he does.

1926
01:42:53,567 --> 01:42:56,798
Buddy Love, as mean
as he tried to play him...

1927
01:42:56,837 --> 01:42:58,532
That's good for you.

1928
01:42:58,572 --> 01:43:02,201
Buddy Love is loveable,
as much as he wanted him not to be.

1929
01:43:02,242 --> 01:43:04,506
Harrelson: If you didn't know
it was Jerry Lewis

1930
01:43:04,545 --> 01:43:06,479
and you just met
both of those guys,

1931
01:43:06,513 --> 01:43:09,073
you wouldn't know
that it was the same person.

1932
01:43:09,116 --> 01:43:11,710
So it's amazing
how he created

1933
01:43:11,752 --> 01:43:14,312
those two completely
distinct characters.

1934
01:43:14,354 --> 01:43:18,552
I don't want to be
something that I'm not.

1935
01:43:18,592 --> 01:43:21,254
I didn't like
being someone else.

1936
01:43:21,295 --> 01:43:24,264
He's just a guy who truly
understands the material

1937
01:43:24,298 --> 01:43:27,392
and he can just go to the depth
that he needs to go

1938
01:43:27,434 --> 01:43:30,494
to make it really, you know,

1939
01:43:30,537 --> 01:43:32,767
touching and emotional.

1940
01:43:32,806 --> 01:43:35,604
